Predicting Trajectories of Agricultural Industries Using Economic Measures and Operator Demographics¶

Harper Lyon

https://harplyon.github.io/CMPS6790FinalTutorial/

Guiding Questions:¶

The mythology of Small Farmers vs Big Ag is familiar to many Americans, but like any element of the American mythology we should be somewhat suspicious - especially when politicians and economicists claim that their new policies will help (or even "save") small farms. Today we'll be trying to get a data based answer to the question of what factors actually have an impact on the fate of the American agricultural industry, which is obviously a moderately well studied question. While we might not be able to match the quality of analysis of the USDA we can at least use their data and learn a bit about data science as we go. There are two main questions that we'll be asking:

  • What measures (like Government payments to farmers, taxes, debt, etc) tell us whether an agricultural industry grows or slows in general?
  • What measures tell us whether the relative share of small farmers vs big ag operations will go up or down?

To attempt to answer these questions we'll be using data both from the USDA directly and from the Agricultural Resource Management Survey, which gives us a chance to do both some classic webscraping and to use a real web API. From the USDA we'll take high quality data from the USDA census on the value of different agricultural industries in each state, and the ARMS survey will tell us more about basically any economic indicator we could ask for, but it is more limited in scope as it only covers 15 states and is inherently less reliable due to its status as a voluntary survey.

The ultimate goal is to combine this data and use it to create a linear regression model for predicting the change in agricultral productivity and farm size* over the years. From there (assuming we get an accurate model) we can extract the coefficients to analyze the relationship of each indicator in our data to both measures. The ideal outcome here is the ability to say that "In our linear model the Tax rate has a coefficient of -10, so we can see that high taxes predict low or no growth in an agricultural sector", but we've got a lot of work until we get there.

There are a few steps to cleaning here, let's start by dropping all columsn we don't need, all of which are either single valued (e.d. Period), empty (e.g. Week Ending), or essential duplicates of other columns (e.g. State ANSI). Note that this step doesn't actually remove any information from the data set - we're strictly getting rid of duplicate or empty data. Also, on a programming level, notice that we can just do this by simply grabbing the handful of columns we do want. This leaves us with the following data:

  • Year: The year of the census this data is from.
  • State: The state this data is from.
  • Domain Category: The (badly titled - we'll fix that soon) NAICS classification of the crop this data represents.
  • Value: The value of the crop from the state in a particular year.

So, we now have the data we actually care about for this column, but it's still not perfect - what even is an NAICS class? Well NAICS is simply a set of codes that the government uses to denote specific industries. Anything that starts with 11 is Agriculture, 111 is crops (vegetable, fruits, ect), 112 livestock, etc. This goes on to very high level of specificity, for instance 111110 is Soybeans, and 111120 is non-soybean oilbeans. The real question of this data cleaning stage is how to handle NAICS - we could compress everything to fairly high level categories (say 4 digits, this would be on the level of Grain, Vegetable, Hog, Cattle, etc) and drop all other data - this has the advantage of reducing the size of our dataset and being easy to translate NAICS codes. We could also translate each individual NAICS code to get a more granular break down. Eventually we'll want to do the later, but handling each code is a lot of work - for the purposes of exploration let's just translate the four digit codes and create a condensed dataframe.

In [8]:
sales_df = sales_df.loc[[len(code) == 4 for code in sales_df['NAICS']]].copy()
sales_df.reset_index(inplace=True)

With this we're almost done, just have to deal with the typing on the Value column - currently that's strings because of some "(D)" values. In the dataset that means that the USDA isn't publishing the data because it would compromise the details of an operation - usually because there's only one, say, citrus orchard in Alaska. We got rid of most of those when we compressed the dataset into just the major categories, but there are still a few. We'll replace those with NaN - this might not be the best approach if we wanted to do real predictive work, but for exploration purposes it's fine.

Agricultural Resource Management Survey Data¶

If we want to do anything more interesting than look at sales we need to know more about the ways that farms are operating which leads us to ARMS, a massive survey run each year to gather data on Farmer income, expenses, demographics, and many other categories of information. We'll specifically be accessing information on government support of farms (in the form of direct payments, favorable loans, etc.) and the average taxes paid by farms - again all broken down by state and industry. This data is accessed through a RESTFUL API, so we'll be using the python requests library in a slightly more advanced way. The instructions and information for the ARMS API is all available at this website. Let's start by making requests for the following information sets:

  • Total payments from government programs to farms per state per industry.
  • Average gross taxes paid by farms per state per industry.
  • The Average Cost to Dept ratio for each farm.
  • Average Liabilities (debt) for each farm.
  • Average Labor Cost per farm.
  • Average Gross Income per farm.
  • Percentage of Operators who own the entirety of their farm.
  • Percentage of Operators who partially own their farms (think someone who owns their home and part of the land they farm but rents additional acreage)
  • Percentage of Operators who are purely renters, and are therefore essentially tenant farmers.
  • Percentage of Operators who have a college degree.
  • Percentage of Operators who don't have a high school diploma.

Note that one of these values is more important than the others - the average gross income per farm. This value is especially important to our analysis because we're going to use it as a proxy for farm size. Obtaining good data on the relative farm size in each industry/state has proven quite difficult, so we're going to focus on average income with the rationale that high average income means that the average farm is big, and low means the average farm is small. This is obviously an imperfect metric, but it's the best I've found so far.

survey_df = functools.reduce(lambda a, b : pd.merge(a, b, on=['Year', 'State', 'Category'], how='outer'), all_requests)

Alright we're down to one frame now. First thing we need to do is get the Payments column into full dollar values (as it is in sales), which is just a matter of multiplying all values by 1000. All the other columns already operate in dollars (or dollars / farm), so it isn't clear why only government payments are measured in thousands. Just goes to show you should always be careful about units. Of course, it won't matter much once we standardize all these values, but until then it's good to have consistent units.

Joining¶

We now need to combine these two datasets, which means deciding which columns (if any) we'll be matching and making sure they're ready to match up. In this case we're going to match on three values - year, state, and category. We're going to focus on changing the survey data to match the sales data - though we could easily choose to do the reverse. Some of these edits are easy, year already matches and state is just a matter of capitalization, but matching categories is harder. Let's perform that easy change and take a closer look at the two category value sets.

Here we need to make some decisions on how to match up these categories. Below is how I'll be mapping each category that doesn't have a clear 1-1 mapping (i.e. Hogs to Hog):

  • General Cash Grains, Wheat, Corn, Soybean -> Oilseed and Grain
  • Other Field Crops, Tobacco, Cotton, Peanuts -> Other Crops
  • Dairy -> Cattle

This leaves us with the categories 'All other livestock' and 'Specialty Crops (F, V, N)' (stands for Fruit, Vegetable, Nut), which have the problem of spanning multiple categories in the USDA dataset. Since we have no way of dividing these, we have a two real choices - we can drop the entries entirely, leading to us having no data to augment those categories in the sales data (note that this is already going to happen to Aquaculture which is not included in the survey) or we can combine the categories in the USDA data (e.g. merge Vegetable and Melon, Fruit and Tree Nut, and Greenhouse, Nursery, and Floriculture'). Let's make an informed decision - how much data would we be losing or combining?

Turns out when you're dealing with an fundamentally combinatorial dataset (there is one and only one entry for each possibility of year, state, and category in the sales data), you're not going to get a better deal with a smaller dataset. I think this is a reasonable merge to perform, as the alternative is to drop more than a third of our total data which I'm just not willing to do at this stage. Hopefully the ARMS folks were onto something by grouping together these categories. So we now have to perform transformations on both frames to prepare for the merge - we have to translate then merge (via groupby) the various categories in both sales_df and survey_df.

In [20]:
#Translation scheme for sales data categories
sales_translation = {'Vegetable and Melon' : 'Specialty Crop', 'Fruit and Tree Nut' : 'Specialty Crop', 'Greenhouse, Nursery, and Floriculture' : 'Specialty Crop',
                     'Sheep and Goat' : 'Other Animals'}

#Applying translation and merging the new categories into each other
sales_df['Category'] = sales_df['Category'].map(lambda x : sales_translation.get(x, x))
sales_df = sales_df.groupby(['Year', 'State', 'Category'])['Value'].sum().reset_index()

That's the sales data done - pretty straightforward. The survey data is a bit trickier because we're translating more categories and also have to be merge more variables for the final data. Pay particular attention to how we aggregate different values differently - total values like Payments get summed, while average or per farm columns (pretty much everything else) gets averaged (since it doesn't really make sense to just add averages together).

#Because of the high degree of redundancy in the translations a function is prefered to a dictionary here
def translate_survey_category(cat):
    if cat in ['General Cash Grains', 'Wheat', 'Corn', 'Soybean']:
        return 'Oilseed and Grain'
    if cat in ['Other Field Crops', 'Tobacco, Cotton, Peanuts']:
        return 'Other Crops'
    if cat in ['Cattle', 'Dairy']:
        return 'Cattle'
    if cat == 'Hogs':
        return 'Hog'
    if cat == 'Specialty Crops (F,V,N)':
        return 'Specialty Crop'
    if cat == 'All other livestock':
        return 'Other Animals'
    return cat

#translating categories

Exploratory Analysis¶

We now have about 300 instances of data which range over fifteen states and cover a variety of measurements. However, to answer our two main questions - which both cover changes from one census year to the other - we need to do some comparative measurements. That's why the first step in our model prep is to add two new values to each observation from 2007 and 2012 - the change in both total value and avg gross income. This is a little bit tricky, so we're going to write a function to take care of it:

In [25]:
def calc_change_in_values(row, df):
    #first we have to check to see if there is a next census year - if not we just report nan
    type(row)
    if row['Year'] == 2017:
        return (np.nan, np.nan)
    #find the next census year relative to the row
    next_year = 2012 if row['Year'] == 2007 else 2017

    #find the row corresponsind to the next years data - this is a bit hacky and should not be copied
    next_row = df.loc[(df['Year'] == next_year) & (df['State'] == row['State']) & (df['Category'] == row['Category'])]
    next_value = next_row.values[0][3]
    next_gross = next_row.values[0][9]

    change_value = (next_value - row['Value']) / row['Value'] if row['Value'] != 0 else np.nan
    
    return (change_value, (next_gross - row['Avg Gross']) / row['Avg Gross'])

change_values = [calc_change_in_values(row[1], ag_df) for row in ag_df.iterrows()]
ag_df['Change Value'] = [c[0] for c in change_values]
ag_df['Change Avg Gross'] = [c[1] for c in change_values]
#now we can safely cut off all the 2017 data

First Modeling Attempt - Full Regression Models¶

Model Prep¶

To reiterate from the intro, our goal here is to figure out what economic factors are relevant to both the overall direction of agricultural industries (in terms of raw production) and also the balance of small farm vs "Big Ag", for which we're using average gross income as a proxy (under the logic that large average income means large average farm size), so at the end of the day what I'm really interested in is the coefficients on our linear model, since those should tell us about the relative importance of the different factors found in our data.

However, this doesn't mean we don't care about accuracy: we need our regression to perform well as a way to validate the coefficients so let's get into it. First thing we need to do is standardize our data (especially important as we have a mix of units and magnitudes). We're going to use z-scoring here since its a good one size fits all approach, but we'll have to keep in mind a few limitations. Most importantly we no longer have meaningful units, so our interpretation is going to be by necessity a bit more limited.

Let's at least see what happens (especially since running models is pretty easy) but if this doesn't work we'll have to take a step back and be a bit more clever about which data we drop and how complex we make our models.

Linear Regression¶

Caveats aside, let's go ahead and try a bog standard linear model on these ten variables. We'll define a test-train split on each target variable and then train a linear regression model from sklearn on the training set:

So overall our accuracy isn't great, but we can learn a bit more from this attempt than that. Observe the following:

  • Test error is generally (except for the Change in Value model) about twice that of training error, which is symptomatic of some overfitting.
  • The score on the Change in Income model may appear better than than the other models, but we can see from the high error that the model is not actually signifigantly better - this is likely a result of a particularily lucky train-test split.

Both of these, and the general variance of these models, is symptomatic of a bad fit of model hypothesis. Now, there are two possilbe reasons for this - it could be that we just dont' have data (which is the more reasonable explanation), or maybe the linear hypothesis just isn't a good one here. This is almost certainly a data problem, but let's try a non-linear model first just to check.

Polynomial Regression¶

To my eye our data - while clearly effectively linear - is also not really "naturally" polynomial in shape, and we probably don't have enough data to fit a ton more features, but we can try and confirm these hypothesis. The majority of our preprocessing is done, so this is fairly straightforward - esepecially since we can actually use a bit of a trick and just train another set of linear regression on augmented data. The idea here is that we can add the polynomial terms directly into our data as new variables which allows a linear regression to approximate a polynomial function.

Using this method of polynomial regression also lets us easily control the degree and therefore the complexity of the hypothesis space, which is particularly important in a data poor enviroment like we're in right now. Of course, sklearn can do this more or less off the shelf:

Y_avg = ag_df['Avg Gross']
y_change_total = ag_df['Change Value']

'''

# we're going to start with polynomial features of degree 2 and see how that does
poly_X = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, include_bias=True)

Now we could use sklearn to do all these models, but like any good programmer I'm going to borrow some code that already does this job (of running and comparing linear regressions on a bunch of single variables) from Dr. Nick Mattei (code taken from this notebook) and making some small modifications - no need to reinvent the wheel. This also lets us look at how a different python library handles this sort of modeling since we'll be using scipy rather than sklearn.

In [41]:
def regress_with_stats(df, observations, target):
  fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, len(observations), figsize=(24,8), sharex=False)

  for i,o in enumerate(observations):
      temp_df = df[[target, o]].dropna()
      slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(temp_df[o],
                                                                     temp_df[target])
      # Pack these into a nice title
      diag_str = "p-value=%.1g\nr-value=%.3f\nstd err.=%.3f\nslope=%.3f\nintercept=%.3f" % (p_value, r_value, std_err, slope, intercept)
      temp_df.plot.scatter(x=o, y=target, title=diag_str, ax=ax[i])
      y_pred = df[o] * slope + intercept
      # Make points and line
      pts = np.linspace(temp_df[o].min(), temp_df[o].max(), 500)
      line = slope * pts + intercept
      ax[i].plot(pts, line, lw=1, color='red')

Alright with that function stolen/defined/modified, we can get to regressing. This is going to be a lot of graphs, so I'll break them up by target variable. In each section we'll do two batches of graphs - one for money based data (government payments, debt, etc) and one for info about farmers (how many rent, level of education, etc). If you don't want to look at all the graphs (and who could blame you) I recommend checking out the models for Total Industry Value and Change in Average Income, which I think present the most interesting results.

Total Industry Value:¶

In [42]:
regress_with_stats(ag_df, ['Payments', 'Taxes', 'Cost Income Ratio', 'Liability', 'Labor'], 'Value')

Here we have our first sucess! The raio of $\frac{\text{average government payments}}{\text{average farm income}}$ has a moderate positive predictive effect on the total value of that industry. This of course should not be surprising - large industries attract more government attention and support, and have more power to lobby for subsidies and other payments, but its good to finally get some value out of this data. The other linear models here are not as interesting, and despite some low p-values on the Taxes and Cost Income Ratio data I'm not convinced by either.

In [43]:
regress_with_stats(ag_df, ['Full Owners', 'Part Owners', 'Renters', 'No High School', 'College Graduates'], 'Value')

No amazing surprises here - but we do have some good results on Full Owners and Part Owners. It seems that the more farmers own their whole farm the lower the total value of the industry tends to be. The intial intuitive hypothesis here would probably be something about how larger, more profitable industries tend to be run centrally by agricultural corporations leading to fewer full owners in those industries. We see a similar pattern, though a little less well founded, in Renter rates. Unfortunately education level doesn't seem to be hugely influential here.

Conclusions¶

Takeaways¶

So, what did we learn through our two passes at modeling/analyzing this data? Well on the data science best practices/meta side I think there's one major takeaway from each of the two modeling attempts:

  1. We - specifically because of ARMS - do not have complete enough data to do even moderately complicated modeling, so attempting to take the easy way out and just toss all the data into an sklearn model went nowhere.
  2. There are some genuine trends and correlations within the data we do have, even if there are only a few such variables.

As for takeaways about the agriculture, I think we can sum up the signifigant relationships from the univariate regression as such:

  • Total Industry Value:
    • Strongly positively predicted by high government payments.
    • Weakly negatively predicted by full ownership of farms/positively with partial ownership and rentier rates (since these are complements)
  • Average Farm Income:
    • Overall much less predictable with our data, but somewhat negatively predicted by average farm debts/income ratio.
  • Change of Total Value over census periods:
    • Very difficult to predict with current data, some promise in farm owernship/education data but not much. This is unfortunate since this would be the prediction that you could make money from.
  • Change of Average Farm Income over census periods:
    • This is the portion of the analysis I find the most interesting, since this says that most about how relative size of farms and the makeup of agriculture changes over time. Most interesting is that we actually find some ability to predict this despite the fact that we get nonsense for change in total value.
    • We see positive relationships with all economic indicators except government payments, which is kind of the opposite of the trend I expected initially - this might be explainable by high labor costs, debt, and taxes leading to lower performing farms closing, raising the average income but we don't have enough data to say.
    • Operator information was not predictive, which I also wasn't expecting. This is a little disappointing, as I'd love to be able to talk about how different operators lead to changes in how industries operate, but it just isn't there.

Possible Future Work¶

When I say future work here of course I don't mean things that I, or you as reader should literally do in the future, but it's often helpful to think about what the current data and analysis suggests would be possible or interesting if we just had more/better data or time to try more models. I think a few questions are suggested by what we've found here:

  1. What would make it possible to predict overall growth in an industry? We had some sucess looking at changes in average income, but none of the data seemed to be completely unrelated to overall growth/loss. This would probably involve bringin in both more and different data, but as I mentioned this is probably the most "real world" applicable measure.
  2. What's happening when we see changes in average income but not the overall value of an industry? Is this due to farms closing, merging, learning how to do better tax evasion or what? This could probably answered using most of the data we have, with maybe some additional digging into the ARMS and USDA data to supply information about the number of farms and such, and would be a fairly straightforward addition to this work.
  3. What happened with Goat/Sheep/Other farming in North Carolina between 2012 and 2017?
